+# CVE-2026-53461 — Not applicable to bullseye (ImageMagick 6.9.11.60+dfsg)
+
+## Summary
+
+CVE-2026-53461 is an out-of-bounds heap write in the ICON reader
+(`coders/icon.c`), in the function `Read1XImage()`, which handles the legacy
+**Windows 1.x icon** format. The fix changes the scanline loop bound from
+`image->columns` to `image->rows` so that non-square 1.x icons no longer write
+past the row buffer.
+
+**This vulnerability is not present in the version Debian bullseye ships
+(`8:6.9.11.60+dfsg-1.3+deb11u13`).** The upstream patch cannot be applied and
+no patching is required.
+
+## Why it does not apply
+
+- The vulnerable function `Read1XImage()` did **not exist** in ImageMagick
+  6.9.11.60. It was introduced by a later refactor of `coders/icon.c` that
+  added support for the Windows 1.x icon format (it is present in, e.g.,
+  6.9.12.98, but absent in 6.9.11.60).
+- In 6.9.11.60, `ReadICONImage()` rejects anything with a non-zero `reserved`
+  header field and only accepts `resource_type` 1 (icon) or 2 (cursor). The
+  Windows 1.x dispatch (`reserved == 0x0001/0x0101/0x0201 -> Read1XImage`) does
+  not exist, so the vulnerable code path is unreachable.
+- The mask/scanline loops that *do* exist in 6.9.11.60 already iterate over
+  `image->rows`, so the out-of-bounds write pattern described by the CVE is not
+  present.
+
+## Action taken
+
+Replaced the upstream patch with an empty `dummy.patch` (no-op), following the
+same convention used for other not-applicable CVEs in this hook (e.g.
+CVE-2023-34152). This records that the CVE was reviewed and intentionally
+classified as not affecting bullseye.
+
+## References
+
